  "docs": {
    "sections": [
      {
        "kind": "summary",
        "title": "Summary",
        "blocks": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "Computes the matrix product."
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "This function is Array API compatible, contrary to\n:func:`numpy.matmul`."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "kind": "parameters",
        "title": "Parameters",
        "items": [
          {
            "name": "x1",
            "type": "array_like",
            "desc_blocks": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "text": "The first input array."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "name": "x2",
            "type": "array_like",
            "desc_blocks": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "text": "The second input array."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "kind": "returns",
        "title": "Returns",
        "items": [
          {
            "name": "out",
            "type": "ndarray",
            "desc_blocks": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "text": "The matrix product of the inputs.\nThis is a scalar only when both ``x1``, ``x2`` are 1-d vectors."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "kind": "examples",
        "title": "Examples",
        "blocks": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "For 2-D arrays it is the matrix product:"
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> a = np.array([[1, 0],\n...               [0, 1]])\n>>> b = np.array([[4, 1],\n...               [2, 2]])\n>>> np.linalg.matmul(a, b)\narray([[4, 1],\n       [2, 2]])"
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "For 2-D mixed with 1-D, the result is the usual."
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> a = np.array([[1, 0],\n...               [0, 1]])\n>>> b = np.array([1, 2])\n>>> np.linalg.matmul(a, b)\narray([1, 2])\n>>> np.linalg.matmul(b, a)\narray([1, 2])"
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "Broadcasting is conventional for stacks of arrays"
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> a = np.arange(2 * 2 * 4).reshape((2, 2, 4))\n>>> b = np.arange(2 * 2 * 4).reshape((2, 4, 2))\n>>> np.linalg.matmul(a,b).shape\n(2, 2, 2)\n>>> np.linalg.matmul(a, b)[0, 1, 1]\n98\n>>> sum(a[0, 1, :] * b[0 , :, 1])\n98"
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "Vector, vector returns the scalar inner product, but neither argument\nis complex-conjugated:"
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> np.linalg.matmul([2j, 3j], [2j, 3j])\n(-13+0j)"
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "Scalar multiplication raises an error."
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> np.linalg.matmul([1,2], 3)\nTraceback (most recent call last):\n...\nValueError: matmul: Input operand 1 does not have enough dimensions ..."
          }
        ]
      },
